    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-04-12T15:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-04-12T15:41:00-05:00" n="213"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">504.418A2/278: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Diekema</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-04-12T21:00:00+00:19"
                            >April 12, 1930—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 12—7:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>73. [From Miller.] Conference 38. There were two plenary sessions of the
                    Conference on April 12.<note n="16" xml:id="d213fn16">League of Nations, <hi
                            rend="italic">Acts of the Conference for the Codification of
                            International Law</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 50,
                        55.</note> At the morning session the somewhat elaborate report of the
                    commission on the territorial waters was received. There were then adopted
                    without dissent three recommendations: The first related to future work of
                    codification; the second to the international régime of ports; the third to the
                    protection of products of the sea.</p>
                <p>All of these appear to be harmless and I shall not cable their text in full
                    unless you request it.</p>
                <p>The afternoon session was devoted to the signing of five documents namely: The
                    nationality convention; protocol relating to military obligations; protocol
                    relating to case of statelessness; special protocol relating to statelessness;
                    and the Final Act of the Conference.</p>
                <p>Of course we signed neither the convention nor any one of the protocols. After
                    consideration we thought the form of the Final Act proper and constituting
                    merely a formal record and in no way binding as an agreement in any sense.
                    Accordingly the Final Act was signed on behalf of the United States by our four
                        delegates,<note n="17" xml:id="d213fn17">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 138.</note> Flournoy having left. Therefore
                        [<hi rend="italic">Thereupon?</hi>] the Conference finally adjourned.
                    Miller.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Diekema</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
